{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"da9904d6-6ede-4da3-b8ef-168f9ac5e963","content":"`SafeAreaEdges` isn't the property you need. There are two separate things to address:\n\n**iOS** — Disable safe-area insets with the platform-specific property:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage\n    xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n    ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"\n    NavigationPage.HasNavigationBar=\"False\"\n    Shell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\">\n\n    <Image Source=\"photo.jpg\" Aspect=\"AspectFill\" />\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\n**Android** — .NET 10 targets Android 15+ where apps are edge-to-edge by default, but the system bars may still have opaque backgrounds. Make them transparent in your `MainActivity`:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)\n{\n    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);\n\n    Window!.SetStatusBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n    Window!.SetNavigationBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"` is the iOS equivalent of what you were trying to do\n- Hide the nav bar (`NavigationPage.HasNavigationBar` or `Shell.NavBarIsVisible`) — it takes space even when transparent\n- On Android, `WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window, false)` is already the default on API 35+, so you just need transparent bar colors","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"aefea6da-ec7c-4b66-b208-1d53ded12d92","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making content go edge-to-edge in a .NET MAUI app, going behind the status bar and navigation bar. They've tried `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the ContentPage but still have padding.\n\nThis is a common .NET MAUI question. Let me check if there's relevant documentation or code in this repository that might help, but given the context, I can likely answer this directly.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, to achieve true edge-to-edge content:\n\n1. `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the ContentPage is not a standard MAUI property - this might be confused with something else, or it might be a newer API. Actually, in .NET MAUI, there isn't a built-in `SafeAreaEdges` property on ContentPage by default. \n\n\n2. The approach differs by platform: on Android in .NET 9+, apps are edge-to-edge by default due to Android 15 requirements, but you still need to manage safe area insets; on iOS, you'll need to use platform-specific properties like `ios:Page.IgnoreSafeArea` or similar to handle the safe area properly. For Android, I need to make the status and navigation bars transparent to achieve the edge-to-edge effect. I'm also wondering if newer .NET MAUI versions like .NET 10 have introduced a unified `SafeAreaEdges` property, though the standard approach still relies on platform-specific configuration for iOS and Android respectively. safe area APIs. But the user's problem is that they still see padding even with their attempted fix.\n\nThe most likely answer:\n\n1. On **iOS**, you need `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"` (not `SafeAreaEdges`)\n2. On **Android** (.NET 9+/Android 15), apps are edge-to-edge by default, but you may need to set transparent system bars. The system applies insets that create padding. You need to handle `WindowInsets` properly or set the status bar/navigation bar to transparent.\n\nActually for .NET 10 MAUI, I believe there's also a `HideSoftInput` and edge-to-edge improvements. Let me give a comprehensive answer.\n\nThe most common issues:\n\n1. **Wrong property**: `SafeAreaEdges` might not exist or might not do what they think. The iOS-specific property is `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"`.\n\n2. **Android system bars**: Even with edge-to-edge, system bars may have colored backgrounds. Need to make them transparent.\n\n3. **Shell padding**: If using Shell, there might be additional padding from the Shell chrome.\n\nFor a photo viewer going truly edge-to-edge, I'm setting up the XAML with the proper iOS safe area configuration disabled, navigation bars hidden, and an image filling the entire viewport.\n\nNow I need to address the Android side—setting the status and navigation bars to transparent and ensuring the app draws behind them, which requires platform-specific code in the Android project.","outputTokens":1695,"requestId":"9BD2:11AB75:625CDFB:6D9FB56:69EC1103"},"id":"68802e9a-9d4e-4001-838b-1438e88fcc12","timestamp":"2026-04-25T00:56:01.883Z","parentId":"e6a60e5f-27be-49bb-9fd5-a59707fcfb00"}
